    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The primary reasons for the overrepresentation of certain racial groups in the US prison system are rooted in the inherent flaws of the American justice system. For instance, African Americans are disproportionately represented due to systemic racism, mass incarceration policies, and the war on drugs, which have led to harsher sentencing and more aggressive policing practices targeting minority communities. Similarly, Hispanics are overrepresented due to the intersection of poverty, lack of access to quality education, and limited economic opportunities, which often lead to involvement in illicit activities to survive. Meanwhile, Native Americans are disproportionately represented due to historical trauma, cultural suppression, and the legacy of forced assimilation, which has led to intergenerational cycles of poverty and crime.",
